J‘ You wrap 'em up in red tape
and fuck with their head

35:40.180 --> 35:42.922
J‘ You might as well use duct tape
and shoot 'em dead

35:43.058 --> 35:45.265
J‘ So yeah, there ain't really no road home

35:45.394 --> 35:48.056
J‘ Keep the people wherever
you had them flown

35:48.188 --> 35:50.645
J‘ Man, ain't you happy
all the colored folks gone?

35:50.774 --> 35:53.311
J‘ Well, shit, who are you gonna
get to mow your lawn?

35:53.444 --> 35:55.901
J‘ Like the car in my driveway
and the swing on the tree

35:56.030 --> 35:58.897
J‘ All my documentation
got washed out to sea

35:59.033 --> 36:03.868
J‘ Home, home on the range

36:03.996 --> 36:06.578
J‘ Is this buffalo shit I'm stepping in?
Man, that's strange

36:06.707 --> 36:08.914
J‘ Naw, it ain't nothing
but shit from a bull

36:09.043 --> 36:11.625
J‘ When I'm talking about bullshit,
man, you is full

36:11.754 --> 36:13.665
J‘ Funny how you're calling it
"the Road Home"... J‘

36:13.797 --> 36:16.834
— (Muffled music blaring)
— (Bird chirping)

36:16.967 --> 36:19.959
— (Sousaphone solo playing)
- (Dishes rattling)

36:40.491 --> 36:41.697
(Woman) All right.

36:41.825 --> 36:43.611
- (Hangs up phone)
— Where does this go?

36:43.744 --> 36:46.076
Under "correspondence answered."

36:46.205 --> 36:51.199
Councilman Thomas can see you now,
but he has a conference call on the hour.

36:51.335 --> 36:52.916
Thank you.

36:53.045 --> 36:55.001
(Knocks) Knock, knock.

36:56.924 --> 36:58.460
What brings you here?

36:58.592 --> 37:01.174
— | wish it were playoff tickets.
— Isn't that something?

37:01.303 --> 37:03.965
The Saints in an NFC Championship Game
in my lifetime.

37:04.932 --> 37:07.093
Sadly, I got no pull in Chicago.

37:08.018 --> 37:10.259
But I am bearing a gift of a kind.

37:10.396 --> 37:13.809
I'm looking into buying
some real estate in mid—city.

37:13.941 --> 37:15.977
Let's just say I'm following a hunch.

37:16.110 --> 37:17.896
- A hunch?
— You can call it that.

37:18.028 --> 37:20.986
(Laughs) No offense,
but if fellas from Dallas, Texas,

37:21.115 --> 37:23.356
are already getting wind
of plans for lower mid—city,

37:23.492 --> 37:26.529
don't you think it's a little late
to be telling the council president?

37:28.163 --> 37:32.702
Son, I can almost hear the sound
of the file cards turning inside your head.

37:32.835 --> 37:34.996
What else you got in that bag of tricks?

37:35.129 --> 37:36.869
What else?

37:37.005 --> 37:38.836
Brother, I got a million of them.

37:42.302 --> 37:45.135
- Buy me a cappuccino.
— I thought you had a conference call.

37:45.264 --> 37:47.971
She always says that
in case I need an out.

37:51.520 --> 37:53.761
October '05, two months after Katrina,

37:53.897 --> 37:56.684
we got a phone call from one of the residents
of lberville Projects

37:56.817 --> 37:59.524
about a possible police shooting
a few days after the storm.

37:59.653 --> 38:03.271
Leon Seals, 29, body found
in a Crozat Street apartment,

38:03.407 --> 38:06.023
a single gunshot wound to the head,
close—range.

38:06.160 --> 38:09.152
"Undetermined, pending investigation."

38:09.288 --> 38:12.155
Our witness says Seals grew up
in the lberville.

38:12.291 --> 38:15.533
His family evacuated during the storm.
He stayed behind.

38:15.669 --> 38:17.876
Whoa, Mr. Seals.

38:18.714 --> 38:21.797
Arrests for armed robbery,
attempted murder,

38:21.925 --> 38:23.756
intent to distribute.

38:23.886 --> 38:25.877
And this is connected to Abreu...

38:26.013 --> 38:28.925
She says she saw three or four cops
chase Seals into the building.

38:29.057 --> 38:31.594
Then she heard gunshots — two of them.

38:35.022 --> 38:36.808
Can she identify the officers?

38:36.940 --> 38:38.555
If she can, she won't.

38:38.692 --> 38:40.603
I did convince her to walk me back
in the building

38:40.736 --> 38:42.522
and show me where the body had been.

38:42.654 --> 38:44.565
I found these...

38:44.698 --> 38:46.609
.380, semiautomatic.

38:46.742 --> 38:48.778
Holy shit.

38:48.911 --> 38:50.902
Same as Abreu.

38:51.038 --> 38:53.700
— Where is the police report?
— We have yet to locate one.

38:53.832 --> 38:56.039
And I filed for a public record request
a year ago.

39:00.839 --> 39:01.874
(Sighs)

39:02.007 --> 39:03.998
— (Thomas) Cables?
- Computer cables.

39:04.134 --> 39:06.876
You know how many of those
you order in a year?

39:07.012 --> 39:09.048
Three, four hundred thousand a year.

39:09.181 --> 39:11.172
You know how much
you're paying per cable?

39:11.308 --> 39:13.924
Buck—79 to buck—98 per unit.

39:14.061 --> 39:15.926
You know how much you should be paying?

39:16.063 --> 39:17.428
Less than a buck.

39:17.564 --> 39:20.397
So, for being a responsible public servant

39:20.526 --> 39:23.643
and putting the brakes
on some half—assed city procurement

39:23.779 --> 39:26.896
and giving the contract
to a reputable Dallas—based firm

39:27.032 --> 39:29.114
that can supply all your computer cable needs,

39:29.243 --> 39:32.827
you save the city
a quarter of a million a year.

39:34.039 --> 39:36.621
Right off the bat, before I even think
about picking up the phone

39:36.750 --> 39:38.411
and checking you out on this shit,

39:38.544 --> 39:40.330
there's something I need to ask you to do.

39:40.462 --> 39:41.542
Today.

39:41.672 --> 39:42.878
A show of good faith.

39:44.049 --> 39:45.664
Name it.

39:45.801 --> 39:47.792
(People chattering)

39:50.264 --> 39:52.471
(Gate buzzes)

39:52.599 --> 39:54.555
(Gate opens)

40:00.899 --> 40:02.890
Susan said it was a traffic stop.

40:03.026 --> 40:05.483
Yeah, a bad tail—light and bad papers.

40:07.948 --> 40:09.154
No papers?

40:13.787 --> 40:15.448
I'll tell you some other time,

40:15.581 --> 40:17.367
when | get out of here.

40:19.668 --> 40:22.159
Janette, they want to deport me.

40:22.296 --> 40:24.161
That's not gonna happen.

40:24.298 --> 40:25.663
We'll get the bail money raised.

40:25.799 --> 40:30.168
And what we really need is an immigration
lawyer. Susan's got contacts.

40:30.304 --> 40:32.260
Just don't throw a Sazerac at the Sheriff.

40:33.181 --> 40:35.718
Oh, you heard about that?

40:35.851 --> 40:39.184
You are now officially
a living legend of Louisiana.

40:39.313 --> 40:40.803
(Chuckles) Great.

40:40.939 --> 40:42.930
Me and Edwin Edwards.

40:51.199 --> 40:52.905
(Man) Yeah, chasing it now.

40:53.035 --> 40:54.900
You get any more ideas,
let me know, all right?

40:55.037 --> 40:56.402
— Mr. Henry.
- All right.

40:57.664 --> 40:59.495
You must be Nelson.

40:59.625 --> 41:02.116
Oliver told me you was coming,
but he didn't say why.

41:03.337 --> 41:05.453
(Sighs) So this is Pigeon Town?

41:05.589 --> 41:06.624
It's part of it.

41:06.757 --> 41:09.715
And you guys are having
a kind of parade, right?

41:09.843 --> 41:12.175
Second line. We do it every year.

41:12.304 --> 41:15.171
Pigeon Town Steppers.
I'm the president.

41:16.058 --> 41:17.923
You're short on cash
is what I understand.

41:18.060 --> 41:21.427
People have been donating,
but we're still about 2000 short.

41:21.563 --> 41:23.394
And we're down to the wire.

41:23.523 --> 41:25.980
— Supposed to go Sunday.
— Day after tomorrow?

41:26.109 --> 41:28.361
Got the band and everything.

41:28.487 --> 41:32.400
Well, compliments
of Hidalgo & Hidalgo of Dallas, Texas.

41:33.617 --> 41:35.482
Vaya con Dios.

41:39.039 --> 41:40.529
J‘ Let's go to Memphis

41:40.666 --> 41:42.452
J‘ In the meantime, baby

41:44.670 --> 41:48.288
J‘ I want to go to Memphis in the meantime, girl

41:49.466 --> 41:53.084
J‘ I want to go to Memphis
in the meantime, baby

41:53.220 --> 41:54.380
J‘ Yeah

41:55.013 --> 41:58.505
J‘ Talk about Memphis
in the meantime, girl J‘

42:14.616 --> 42:15.731
Whoo!

42:21.456 --> 42:23.833
(Cheering)

42:26.044 --> 42:28.205
See what I mean?

42:28.338 --> 42:29.748
He wrote all of these?

42:29.881 --> 42:31.917
One right after the other.

42:35.303 --> 42:37.385
Thank you so much.

42:37.514 --> 42:40.722
I'm no weatherman,
but I think it feels like rain.

42:40.851 --> 42:42.842
(Cheering and applause)

42:43.937 --> 42:46.394
(J‘ Feels Like Rain)

42:53.447 --> 42:55.403
Mm.

42:58.952 --> 43:01.113
J‘ Down here the river

43:02.789 --> 43:04.654
J‘ Meets the sea

43:11.423 --> 43:14.381
J‘ And in the sticky heat I feel you

43:16.011 --> 43:18.172
J‘ Open up to me

43:23.810 --> 43:25.186
J‘ Love

43:26.730 --> 43:29.346
J‘ Comes out of nowhere, baby

43:32.068 --> 43:34.320
J‘ Just like a hurricane

43:36.573 --> 43:39.315
J‘ And it feels like rain

43:39.451 --> 43:41.487
(Cheering)

43:43.747 --> 43:46.989
J‘ I said, it feels like rain...

43:50.962 --> 43:52.793
(Sighs)

44:09.064 --> 44:12.397
J‘ And it feels like rain

44:12.526 --> 44:18.487
J‘ Rain

44:18.615 --> 44:25.532
J‘ Feels

44:25.664 --> 44:27.746
J‘ Just like rain, feels like rain

44:27.874 --> 44:30.911
J‘ Tip—tap, tip—tapping
on my windowpane

44:33.713 --> 44:36.455
J‘ 'Cause it feels like rain

44:36.591 --> 44:38.877
J‘ Baby, can you feel it?

44:40.345 --> 44:44.213
J‘ Feels like rain, feels like rain

44:44.349 --> 44:46.931
J‘ Feels like rain

44:47.644 --> 44:49.760
J‘ Tip—tap

44:49.896 --> 44:52.433
J‘ 'Cause it feels like rain J‘

44:53.567 --> 44:55.558
(Cheering)

45:02.117 --> 45:03.732
It's a good song.

45:03.869 --> 45:06.656
It's a great song.
But what's great about it?

45:07.914 --> 45:09.450
Thank you.

45:09.583 --> 45:12.040
— (Annie) OK, for starters?
- For starters.

45:12.168 --> 45:13.874
The melody is cool.

45:14.004 --> 45:16.416
You know, it's simple like the blues,

45:16.548 --> 45:19.460
but it's not locked into
those chord changes.

45:19.593 --> 45:21.424
Yeah, the music gives you what it can.

45:21.553 --> 45:23.009
But keep going.

45:23.138 --> 45:26.596
Well, the lyrics — not so simple.

45:27.392 --> 45:31.135
I mean, he starts off
and he's singing about the weather,

45:31.271 --> 45:33.728
the river, the sea, you know.

45:33.857 --> 45:36.439
And you realize it's New Orleans.

45:36.568 --> 45:38.900
But then he isn't singing
about New Orleans.

45:39.029 --> 45:41.270
You know, it's really love
he's got on his mind.

45:41.406 --> 45:42.395
OK.

45:42.532 --> 45:45.365
And love is not simple.

45:45.493 --> 45:47.484
You know, it's a little dark sometimes

45:47.621 --> 45:51.205
— and a little dangerous, like New Orleans.
- Ha!

45:52.000 --> 45:55.333
And he's just riding it out
no matter how rough it gets.

45:57.088 --> 46:00.205
He's like us...
now, after the storm.

46:01.217 --> 46:03.549
Hiatt wrote that song
20 years ago, darling,

46:03.678 --> 46:05.839
when you still had training wheels
on your bike

46:05.972 --> 46:08.759
and nobody had ever heard
the name Katrina.

46:09.809 --> 46:11.140
Really?

46:11.269 --> 46:14.602
That's what makes it a great song.

46:20.612 --> 46:22.603
(J‘ Mama Roux)

46:29.037 --> 46:31.528
J‘ Is your man out of hand?

46:31.665 --> 46:33.997
J‘ Don't come home at night?

46:34.125 --> 46:36.662
J‘ And just because when he does

46:36.795 --> 46:39.252
J‘ He still don't treat you right

46:39.381 --> 46:41.542
J‘ And only love we're speaking of

46:41.675 --> 46:43.916
J‘ The fix is no big thing

46:44.052 --> 46:46.293
J‘ 'Cause for true, Mama Roux

46:46.429 --> 46:48.841
J‘ Can do most anything

46:48.974 --> 46:50.464
J‘ Mama Roux

46:50.600 --> 46:53.467
J‘ Fait la belle hoodoo

46:53.603 --> 46:55.639
J‘ Mama Roux

46:55.772 --> 46:57.512
J‘ Tell your troubles to

46:59.150 --> 47:00.856
J‘ Mama Roux

47:00.986 --> 47:03.853
J‘ Femme of New Orleans

47:03.989 --> 47:05.729
J‘ Mama Roux

47:05.865 --> 47:08.607
J‘ Queen of the hoodoo queens

47:46.197 --> 47:48.188
(Cheering)

47:52.245 --> 47:54.987
(Car stops, engine idling)

47:57.292 --> 47:58.498
(Sighs)

48:02.380 --> 48:04.962
— (Man) Bye.
— Later, guys. Bye.

48:15.351 --> 48:16.932
(Door slams)

48:17.062 --> 48:19.644
I think I'm starting to figure this place out.

48:19.773 --> 48:22.606
It's a village -
a village on an island.

48:22.734 --> 48:24.440
Everyone's connected.

48:24.569 --> 48:28.107
They may love each other. They may
hate each other, but they're all related.

48:28.239 --> 48:31.572
This week I bought an empty building
for a million—one

48:31.701 --> 48:34.693
and laid out a couple grand in a little bitty bar
at the back of town.

48:34.829 --> 48:39.038
Both of them on a handshake
and 'cause somebody told me to.

48:39.167 --> 48:40.998
It's all connected somehow.

48:41.920 --> 48:44.787
And I'm this close to seeing
how it all hooks up.

48:46.674 --> 48:48.665
Let me ask you something, darling.

48:49.636 --> 48:52.378
— You ever been to a second line?
— Sure.

48:52.514 --> 48:54.596
I haven't.

48:58.103 --> 49:01.891
— (Strumming guitar)
— (Annie) J‘ See my shadow on the wall

49:04.692 --> 49:08.935
J‘ It don't look like me at all

49:11.032 --> 49:12.863
(Humming)

49:36.391 --> 49:39.098
J‘ Until Mardi Gras is done... J‘

49:43.481 --> 49:45.346
— Looks great.
— Yeah.

49:46.651 --> 49:48.482
Thank you.

49:51.364 --> 49:53.355
(J‘ Dixieland jazz)

50:13.970 --> 50:14.959
(Door opens)

50:15.096 --> 50:18.463
OK, l have bagels with cream cheese and lox
and coffee.

50:18.600 --> 50:20.716
I'll have coffee.

50:20.852 --> 50:22.683
OK.

50:24.189 --> 50:26.305
How's it going?

50:26.441 --> 50:28.682
I'm gonna finish.

50:28.818 --> 50:31.104
When are we going to Brooklyn?

50:34.324 --> 50:36.315
Dad, I gotta tell you something.

50:36.451 --> 50:37.987
I'm not gonna be ready.

50:38.119 --> 50:40.235
Tell me something I don't know.

50:40.371 --> 50:42.282
I've been sewing, though.

50:48.504 --> 50:50.369
That's it? That's all you got, hmm?

50:50.506 --> 50:52.713
Wait, hold on now.

51:05.939 --> 51:08.146
Someone taught you how to sew, at least.

51:08.274 --> 51:10.265
(Chuckles)

51:11.486 --> 51:13.226
This lndian's missing a few tears.

51:13.363 --> 51:17.231
— That's what them blue rose montees is for?
— Mm—hm.

51:17.367 --> 51:19.699
Mm.

51:19.827 --> 51:21.283
That's not bad.

51:22.247 --> 51:24.078
That's damn good, actually.

51:25.875 --> 51:28.082
Well, too bad you ain't
got a suit to go with it.

51:28.211 --> 51:29.951
Maybe next year.

51:32.382 --> 51:33.792
It's for you, Daddy.

51:34.968 --> 51:36.708
Me?

51:36.844 --> 51:39.176
Yeah, I made it for you.

51:40.974 --> 51:42.680
This lndian...

51:44.644 --> 51:46.680
is you.

51:48.815 --> 51:50.555
This is your house.

51:53.403 --> 51:55.189
And the blue tarp.

52:06.249 --> 52:08.786
l was hoping you'd wear it this year.

52:10.628 --> 52:13.165
I'm hoping you make it out
Mardi Gras day.

52:17.760 --> 52:19.296
You gonna be there?

52:19.429 --> 52:20.635
I told you I would be.

52:20.763 --> 52:22.924
You told me you were sewing too.

52:24.892 --> 52:26.507
l have been.

52:26.644 --> 52:28.600
I'm just slow.

52:40.533 --> 52:42.569
(Doorbell rings)

52:52.587 --> 52:54.327
Mrs. Williams,

52:54.464 --> 52:56.625
is now a good time?

52:56.758 --> 52:58.919
Come in.

52:59.052 --> 53:01.759
— Your husband?
— He's in New Orleans for the day.

53:01.888 --> 53:03.628
My kids are at Sunday school.

53:03.765 --> 53:05.301
I skipped mass.

53:05.433 --> 53:07.094
(Chuckles) Me too.

53:07.226 --> 53:10.013
I tried your cell, thought I'd come up here,
see if I could catch you.

53:10.146 --> 53:13.183
I haven't picked up messages
in a couple of days. Please sit.

53:14.525 --> 53:18.689
I wonder if you wouldn't mind
looking at some photographs.

53:20.073 --> 53:21.938
We arrested a couple of men...

53:22.700 --> 53:26.158
for a similar incident in the same neighborhood
last week.

53:26.287 --> 53:28.824
Yeah, all right.

53:36.381 --> 53:39.748
No, I don't think so.

53:48.559 --> 53:50.595
Oh my God.

53:52.313 --> 53:54.304
— That's them.
— Are you sure?

53:55.566 --> 53:58.399
Damn it. God damn it.

54:00.279 --> 54:02.406
Him and him!

54:04.450 --> 54:05.656
God damn it!

54:05.785 --> 54:08.322
Good. That's who we arrested.

54:08.454 --> 54:11.036
Oh shit.

54:13.709 --> 54:16.576
- (Band playing)
_ (People chattering)

54:30.852 --> 54:32.467
(Cheering)

54:32.603 --> 54:34.594
(Man) Yeah!

55:34.457 --> 55:35.742
(Laughing)

55:37.418 --> 55:39.249
(Man) | see you over there, boy.

55:39.378 --> 55:42.085
Look at bigfoot. He can dance.

55:42.215 --> 55:43.580
So can I.

55:43.716 --> 55:45.081
Yes, you can.

55:45.218 --> 55:49.177
— Colson, you going native on us, huh?
- It looks different from out here.

55:49.305 --> 55:51.261
Yeah, right.
What are you gonna do now?

55:51.390 --> 55:54.132
You gonna quit and go join
the public defender's office or something?

55:54.268 --> 55:56.133
Come on, try it, Lonnie.

55:56.270 --> 55:57.851
Huh?

55:57.980 --> 55:59.686
(Laughing)

56:00.942 --> 56:03.228
- See this guy?
— No? It's not for you?

56:10.618 --> 56:13.735
Hey, I didn't think
this was gonna happen, huh?

56:13.871 --> 56:16.533
A last—minute benefactor, an angel.

56:16.666 --> 56:18.406
I don't know if I approve, you know.

56:18.543 --> 56:20.704
It sets a precedent
for paying the higher fees.

56:20.836 --> 56:22.747
— You wouldn't want this not to happen.
— No.

56:22.880 --> 56:25.838
No, and we will prevail
in court eventually, huh?

56:25.967 --> 56:27.878
That's what I admire about you, Toni,

56:28.010 --> 56:32.549
your faith in the system
despite all your experiences to the contrary.

56:32.682 --> 56:34.547
(Laughs)

56:48.739 --> 56:51.526
Sofia seems to be having a good time.

56:51.659 --> 56:54.651
It's a temporary reprieve.
She is so grounded.

56:54.787 --> 56:57.244
I wouldn't let her out for anything else.

56:57.373 --> 56:59.079
What did she do?

56:59.208 --> 57:01.199
— Broke the rules.
- I know.

57:01.335 --> 57:04.702
(Terry) And people think
you're a bleeding—heart liberal.

57:04.839 --> 57:08.297
Yes, punishment first,
then forgiveness.

57:09.260 --> 57:11.171
Wouldn't that be nice?
